The people in America who were whining about how our covid mitigation efforts was tyranny really look like morons when ACTUAL tyranny happens in China. 

No one is physically forced to get tested in America. No one is literally locked in their homes, and people aren’t practically ignored and left to starve when America locked down. 

Not saying the policies here were harmless and insignificant, but there’s a massive difference between practicing health safety efforts from government by mostly using local state and municipalities, and the state outright banning people from getting food to survive, with no real preparation. 

We should consider ourselves lucky we’re not in an actual authoritarian state, because if we were, we’d be doing what China has done

snippet.textDisplay:
You missed half the story about the situation in China. The Omicron wave did not start in Shanghai and it was the only place hit by it. 

The wave started in Hong Kong, then Shenzhen, Shanghai and Jilin all had outbreaks around the same time. Shenzhen imposed a lockdown early on and it only took them one week. Jilin had a much bigger outbreak but it was also contained. 

It was only in Shanghai that the government tried something that deviated from zero-COVID policy. The central government let them test it for several weeks, and the result was tens of thousands of infections and continuous stream of COVID-infected people spreading it to the other provinces.

People in Shanghai might blame zero-COVID policy for their sufferings, but the rest of China blame Shanghai government for the whole mess. The consensus of the Chinese people, minus Shanghai, is that Omicron can be contained, and that zero-COVID is the right thing to do.

snippet.textDisplay:
Western countries didn't suffer from Covid because of a laissez-faire approach. The entire world has suffered and will continue to suffer because of a too restrictive approach. 

China didn't have deaths in the low thousands. Especially if you count deaths the way they were counted in the US. The covid death total in the US would be much lower if they counted the deaths the way they do for influenza. And China lies about anything it can get away with. Hubei province itself probably had tens if not hundreds of thousands of deaths. Other places were not so seriously hit by covid, though there were more than just a few thousand deaths in China outside Hubei, but you'll never find out the true cost of the covid policy. I am convinced that a friend of mine in China ended up dropping out of college, landing in a mental hospital for a time, and cutting her veins a few times because of the covid lockdowns. I believe it was the stresses and disruptions of the covid lockdown restrictions that drove her that far. She's doing much better now since they were let up. We will be dealing with similar lifelong problems due even to the lesser disruptions to health and education we've created in the West. And if there's an area where we've been a bit laissez-faire it's that.
